Chapter 9: Tree based methods¶

Tree-based models form a broad class of nonparametric learning methods that recursively partition the feature space into smaller, non-overlapping regions that are relatively homogeneous with respect to the response variable. These methods are intuitive, interpretable, and capable of capturing complex structures in the data without relying on strict parametric assumptions.

Advantages using tree-based models:

Flexibility and Interpretability Tree-structured models are extremely flexible, capable of handling both categorical and continuous variables. They provide an intuitive and visual understanding of how predictors influence the response, making them ideal for both exploratory and predictive analyses.

Handling of Complex Interactions Tree-based models automatically account for high-order interactions among predictors. This makes them particularly effective when relationships among variables are complex or involve nonlinear or non-monotonic effects.

Robustness to Data Distribution and Scale Unlike many regression models, decision trees do not assume linear relationships, normality, or homoscedasticity. They are also invariant to monotonic transformations and scaling of predictors.

Ease of Implementation and Minimal Preprocessing Tree-based methods are simple to implement in R (e.g., using the rpart, tree, or caret packages). They require little data preprocessing—no need for variable standardization, transformation, or dummy coding.

Variable Selection and Insight Trees inherently perform variable selection by choosing the most informative predictors for splitting at each node. This can provide valuable insights about which features are most influential and can guide subsequent model refinement.

Adaptability to Various Applications Decision trees are widely used in numerous fields—such as linguistics, biology, finance, and public health—because they perform well with moderate sample sizes and mixed data types.

Tree-based approaches serve as the foundation for several advanced ensemble methods that improve prediction accuracy and stability, including:

Bagging (Bootstrap Aggregation) – e.g., Random Forests

Boosting – e.g., Gradient Boosted Trees (XGBoost, LightGBM)

Random Forests – Combining multiple decision trees built on bootstrapped samples and random subsets of features

Decision Tree¶

A Decision Tree is a popular supervised machine learning algorithm used for both classification and regression tasks. It is a tree-like model consisting of several key components:

  • Root Node: The topmost node in the tree, containing all the training data.
  • Internal Nodes: Subgroups formed through a recursive process using binary partitions. Each internal node represents a feature or attribute, posing simple yes-or-no questions about the features to split the data.
  • Branches: Connections that link the nodes together, representing decision rules or conditions.
  • Leaf Nodes (Terminal Nodes): The terminal subgroups at the bottom of the tree that represent predictions or class labels. The size of a tree is determined by the number of these terminal nodes.
  • Depth: The depth of a tree corresponds to the length of the longest path from the root node to a leaf node.
  • Size: Defined by the number of terminal nodes in the tree.

How Decision Trees Work¶

A Decision Tree recursively partitions the data based on feature values, forming groups that become increasingly homogeneous with respect to the target variable. At each step, the algorithm selects the optimal feature and threshold that minimize impurity (in classification) or reduce prediction error (in regression). This recursive splitting continues until a specified stopping criterion is reached—such as a minimum node size, a maximum tree depth, or no further improvement in purity.

The resulting tree structure is intuitive, interpretable, and easy to visualize. Decision Trees can handle both categorical and numerical predictors and require minimal data preprocessing, as there is no need for variable standardization or dummy coding. Moreover, they provide transparent and easily interpretable decision rules, making them valuable for both exploratory analysis and predictive modeling.

A decision tree is a general framework for representing decision rules through a hierarchical, tree-like structure. It can be applied to both classification and regression problems and encompasses a variety of algorithms including CART.

CART (Classification And Regression Trees)¶

Among the various methodologies for constructing tree-based models, one of the most classical and influential approaches is the Classification and Regression Tree (CART) algorithm, introduced by Breiman, Friedman, Olshen, and Stone (1984). The CART algorithm recursively divides the training data into homogeneous subgroups, or regions of the predictor space where the response values are relatively similar. Within each terminal node (leaf), a constant prediction is assigned—typically the mean of the response for regression or the majority class for classification.

Geometrically, each leaf node corresponds to a hyper-rectangular region of the feature space, defined by a sequence of binary splitting rules on the predictors.

Regression Trees

For a regression tree, the model aims to minimize the Residual Sum of Squares (RSS) across all terminal regions: $$ R(T) = \sum_{j=1}^J\sum_{i:x_i\in R_j}(y_i-\hat{y}_{R_j})^2, $$

[Source: https://bookdown.org/hailiangdu/Lecture_notes/tree-based-models.html]

In practice, to balance between variance and bias and prevent overfitting, we frequently employ the 'weakest link pruning algorithm' to trim trees. The goal is to assess whether a smaller tree can yield comparable results to the fully grown tree. If this is the case, opting for the simpler tree is preferable, as it reduces the risk of overfitting.

The objective function (other similar variant version) with tuning parameter:

$$ R_{cp}(T) ≡ R(T) + c_p |T| R(T_1) $$

where $c_p$ is the tuning parameter (the complexity paramter), and $T_1$ is the tree without any splits.

Classification Trees

For classification problems, the CART algorithm divides the predictor space into regions that are increasingly pure, meaning that most observations within each region belong to a single class.
Instead of minimizing squared error (as in regression trees), CART minimizes a measure of node impurity.

Let $\hat{p}_{mk}$ denote the proportion of training observations in node $m$ that belong to class $k$.
Several impurity measures can be used:

  • Gini Index

    $$ G_m = \sum_{k=1}^{K} \hat{p}_{mk}(1 - \hat{p}_{mk}) $$

  • Cross-Entropy (Deviance)

    $$ D_m = -\sum_{k=1}^{K} \hat{p}_{mk}\log(\hat{p}_{mk}) $$

  • Classification Error Rate

    $$ E_m = 1 - \max_k(\hat{p}_{mk}) $$

Among these, the Gini index and cross-entropy are the most commonly used because they are more sensitive to changes in node purity than the misclassification rate. Both the Gini index and cross-entropy measure how pure or impure a node is ( how mixed the classes are within that node). The Gini index increases as the class proportions become more evenly distributed and decreases as one class dominates. You may think of the Gini index as the expected error rate if you randomly assign class labels according to the observed class probabilities within that node. With the Gini index, CART produce nodes that are more homogeneous. The cross-entropy (also called deviance or information gain) measures the information content or uncertainty in class predictions. The Gini index is often preferred for computational efficiency, while cross-entropy aligns with the concept of information gain used in information theory.

  • If all observations in a node belong to one class, say $\hat{p}_{mk}=1$ for some class $k$, then $G_m = 0$.
    → The node is pure.
  • If classes are perfectly mixed (e.g., for two classes $\hat{p}_{m1} = \hat{p}_{m2} = 0.5$),
    then $G_m = 2(0.5)(0.5) = 0.5$.
    → The node is maximally impure.

Consider a binary classification problem ($K=2$) with class probabilities $(p_1, p_2)$ within a node.
We compare Gini impurity and cross-entropy for three different levels of purity:

Class Distribution Gini Index Cross-Entropy
$(0.5, 0.5)$ $2(0.5)(0.5) = 0.50$ $- [0.5\log(0.5) + 0.5\log(0.5)] = 0.693$
$(0.9, 0.1)$ $2(0.9)(0.1) = 0.18$ $- [0.9\log(0.9) + 0.1\log(0.1)] = 0.325$
$(1.0, 0.0)$ $2(1)(0) = 0.00$ $- [1\log(1) + 0\log(0)] = 0.000$

Both measures decrease as one class becomes dominant (i.e., the node becomes purer).
When the classes are perfectly mixed, both impurity measures reach their maximum values.

# Load package
library(rpart)    # CART implementation

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. Define helper functions for impurity
# ------------------------------------------------------------

# Gini index: measures expected misclassification rate
gini = function(p) {
  p = p[p > 0]                      # ignore zeros
  sum(p * (1 - p))
}

# Cross-entropy (deviance): measures information uncertainty
cross_entropy = function(p) {
  p = p[p > 0]                      # drop zeros to avoid log(0)
  -sum(p * log(p))                  # natural-log entropy
}

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Numerical illustration for binary classification nodes
# ------------------------------------------------------------
p_list = list(
  "Balanced (0.5, 0.5)" = c(0.5, 0.5),
  "Skewed   (0.9, 0.1)" = c(0.9, 0.1),
  "Pure     (1.0, 0.0)" = c(1.0, 0.0)
)

example_df = data.frame(
  Distribution  = names(p_list),
  Gini          = sapply(p_list, gini),
  CrossEntropy  = sapply(p_list, cross_entropy),
  row.names = NULL
)

cat("Numerical illustration (binary):\n")
print(example_df)

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Fit a CART classification tree using the iris dataset
# ------------------------------------------------------------
set.seed(6021)   # reproducibility

fit = rpart(
  Species ~ .,
  data = iris,
  method = "class",
  control = rpart.control(cp = 0.001, minsplit = 5, maxdepth = 5)
)

# Quick visual check of the fitted tree
 rpart.plot::rpart.plot(fit)
text(fit, use.n = TRUE, cex = 0.8)

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Compute node impurity for each terminal node
# ------------------------------------------------------------
node_id = fit$where                   # terminal node ID for each observation
tbl = table(node_id, iris$Species)    # class counts per node

# Convert counts to class probabilities
row_sums = rowSums(tbl)
probs = sweep(tbl, 1, row_sums, FUN = "/")

# Compute Gini and Cross-Entropy for each node
node_gini = apply(probs, 1, function(p) gini(as.numeric(p)))
node_ce   = apply(probs, 1, function(p) cross_entropy(as.numeric(p)))

# Create a tidy summary table
terminal_summary = data.frame(
  NodeID = as.integer(rownames(probs)),
  N = as.integer(row_sums),
  Prob_Setosa = as.numeric(probs[, "setosa"]),
  Prob_Versicolor = as.numeric(probs[, "versicolor"]),
  Prob_Virginica = as.numeric(probs[, "virginica"]),
  Gini = round(node_gini, 4),
  CrossEntropy = round(node_ce, 4)
)

terminal_summary = terminal_summary[order(terminal_summary$NodeID), ]

cat("\nImpurity by terminal node (training data):\n")
print(terminal_summary)

# Cost-Complexity Pruning
# ------------------------------------------------------------
 cp_table = printcp(fit)                      # show cross-validated error
 best_cp = cp_table[which.min(cp_table[,"xerror"]), "CP"]
 fit_pruned = prune(fit, cp = best_cp)        # pruned tree if desired

# Notes:
# - Both Gini and Cross-Entropy decrease as nodes become purer.
# - Cross-Entropy here uses natural log; for base-2 log, divide by log(2).
# - For cleaner visualization, try: rpart.plot::rpart.plot(fit)

The first and most powerful split, Petal.Length < 2.5, completely isolates all setosa flowers, yielding a terminal node with 100% purity and a Gini index of 0, indicating no class uncertainty. The remaining data, consisting of versicolor and virginica, is further divided by Petal.Width < 1.8, which substantially reduces impurity by separating most versicolor samples from virginica. Subsequent fine splits such as Petal.Length < 5 and Petal.Width ≥ 1.6 continue to decrease node impurity until each leaf is nearly pure. This progressive reduction in Gini or cross-entropy impurity at each level of the tree demonstrates how CART efficiently identifies the most informative features and thresholds, leading to a simple yet highly accurate classification rule: setosa is defined by short petals, versicolor by moderate petal width, and virginica by wider petals.

Overall, the result clearly demonstrates that socioeconomic status (lstat) is the dominant predictor of housing value, with structural characteristics (rm) and environmental factors (crim, dis) refining the predictions. Affluent neighborhoods with large homes achieve the highest predicted values, while high-poverty, high-crime areas correspond to the lowest.

Variable Interpretation Effect on Median Value (medv)
lstat % lower-status population Strong negative effect (dominant variable)
rm Average number of rooms Positive effect (more rooms → higher value)
crim Crime rate Negative effect (higher crime → lower value)
dis Distance to employment centers Slight positive effect (more distance → higher value)

It predicts median home value (medv) based on socioeconomic and structural variables. The first and most influential split occurs at lstat = 5.145, where lstat represents the percentage of lower-status population. Neighborhoods with lstat < 5.145 correspond to wealthier areas, yielding the highest predicted home values. Within this group, a further split on rm (average number of rooms per dwelling) shows that areas with larger homes (rm ≥ 7.406) have the greatest median value (around $46.5K), while smaller homes (`rm < 7.406`) predict slightly lower values (around $42.6K). On the other hand, areas with lstat ≥ 5.145 reflect less affluent neighborhoods, and further divisions reveal nuanced socioeconomic and geographic effects. When lstat ≥ 15, house prices drop sharply, especially in high-crime regions (crim ≥ 5.769 -> around $11.9K). For moderate `lstat` levels (between 5.145 and 15), home values depend on housing size and location: more rooms (`rm ≥ 7.011`) and greater distance from industrial centers (`dis ≥ 2.089`) are associated with higher prices (up to around $33K).

#Select the optimal CP (tuning parameter) using R train function

set.seed(527)
#Cross validation :  10 folder cross validation
ctrl  =  trainControl(method  = "cv", number  = 10) 

#Tuning parameter: the complexity parameter (cp), 
#which imposes a penalty to the tree for having two many splits. 
#The default value is 0.01. The higher the cp, the smaller the tree.
#A too small value of cp leads to overfitting and a too large cp value will result to a too small tree. Both cases decrease the predictive performance of the model.
#An optimal cp value can be estimated by testing different cp values and using cross-validation approaches.

#To create the searching grid
tgrid = expand.grid(
 cp= c(0.000001, 0.0001, 0.0002,  0.001, 0.002)
)

fit.rpart1 =  train(medv ~ ., data = train.dat, 
                     method = "rpart", trControl = ctrl, tuneGrid =tgrid) 

fit.rpart1 =  train(medv ~ ., data = train.dat, 
                     method = "rpart", trControl = ctrl, tuneLength =10)

#rpart :  Recursive Partitioning and Regression Trees  
#rpart is another name of CART in R
#build a CART on the training data
library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Build a CART model on the training data
# ------------------------------------------------------------
fit.rpart = rpart(
  diabetes ~ .,           # response and predictors
  data = dat,             # dataset
  method = "class",       # "class" for classification, "anova" for regression
  control = rpart.control(
    cp = 0.001,           # complexity parameter (controls pruning)
    minsplit = 10,        # minimum number of observations to attempt a split
    maxdepth = 6          # maximum depth of the tree
  )
)


#To show the regression tree 
plot(fit.rpart)
text(fit.rpart, digits = 3)

# Clear, readable plot
rpart.plot(
  fit.rpart,
  type = 2,             # 0 = label below node, 2 = label inside node
  extra = 106,          # show class, prob, and % observations
  under = TRUE,         # add text under the boxes
  faclen = 0,           # do not abbreviate factor levels
  box.palette = "GnBu", # color scale (Blue-Green)
  branch.lty = 3,       # dashed branches
  shadow.col = "gray",  # add shadow for clarity
  cex = 0.8,            # control text size
  main = "CART Classification Tree for Diabetes Data"
)

The first and most influential split occurs at glucose = 128, clearly identifying blood glucose as the dominant predictor of diabetes. Individuals with glucose levels below 128 are mostly classified as non-diabetic (neg), especially if they are younger and have lower body mass, indicating that low glucose combined with healthy weight and age strongly corresponds to a negative diagnosis. In contrast, those with glucose ≥ 128 are more likely to be diabetic (pos), and their risk further increases with higher BMI, insulin levels, or lower age. The rightmost branches of the tree, representing individuals with both very high glucose (≥ 158) and elevated insulin (≥ 630), with predicted probabilities above 0.85 for diabetes, indicating almost certain positive cases. Overall, the tree demonstrates that glucose concentration is the most critical variable in predicting diabetes, while BMI, age, and insulin serve as important secondary modifiers that refine the model’s predictive accuracy.

# ------------------------------------------------------------
#    - minsplit:  node must have ≥ this many rows to consider a split
#    - minbucket: each terminal (leaf) must have ≥ this many rows
#    - maxdepth:  maximum number of splits from root to any leaf
#    - cp:        minimum relative improvement required to split
# ------------------------------------------------------------
cntrl = rpart.control(
  minsplit = 10,
  minbucket = 3,
  maxdepth = 20,
  cp = 0.001
)

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Fit the CART classifier
# ------------------------------------------------------------
fit = rpart(
  diabetes ~ .,
  data = dat,
  method = "class",
  control = cntrl
)

# ------------------------------------------------------------
# Predictions and Confusion Matrix (on the same data)
#    Note: evaluating on training data inflates accuracy.
# ------------------------------------------------------------
yhat = predict(fit, newdata = dat, type = "class")

# Ensure the prediction factor has the same level order as the truth
yhat = factor(yhat, levels = levels(dat$diabetes))

cm = confusionMatrix(data = yhat, reference = dat$diabetes)
cm

Option What it does Example / Tip
type Controls the layout of labels and nodes type = 1 – labels below nodes (default)
type = 2 – labels inside boxes (cleaner)
extra Adds more info inside nodes extra = 101 – class only
extra = 104 – class + prob
extra = 106 – class + prob + % obs
fallen.leaves Aligns all leaf nodes at the bottom fallen.leaves = TRUE for a neat look
box.palette Color scheme for class purity Try "GnBu", "Blues", "RdYlGn", or "Greens"
cex Text size cex = 0.8 (smaller) or cex = 1.2 (larger)
tweak Scales the whole diagram tweak = 1.2 makes boxes slightly larger
branch.lty Line type for branches branch.lty = 3 makes dashed lines

#to tune multiple parameters like cp, minsplit, and maxdepth together, you’ll need to write a custom loop or use tuneGrid with a wrapper that builds the tree manually. For example:

grid = expand.grid(
  cp = c(0.001, 0.005, 0.01),
  minsplit = c(5, 10, 20),
  maxdepth = c(5, 10, 15)
)

results = data.frame()

for (i in 1:nrow(grid)) {
  cntrl = rpart.control(
    minsplit = grid$minsplit[i],
    maxdepth = grid$maxdepth[i],
    cp = grid$cp[i]
  )
  
  fit = rpart(diabetes ~ ., data = train.dat, method = "class", control = cntrl)
  pred = predict(fit, newdata = test.dat, type = "class")
  acc = mean(pred == test.dat$diabetes)
  
  results = rbind(results, data.frame(grid[i, ], Accuracy = acc))
}

results
